    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## QUESTION 1\n",
        "\n",
        "__Use the provided code above to read in the batting table. Then, with Python Polars manipulate the 'results' dataframe to calculate the number of at bats and the batting average for each year a player played. Filter the data frame to only include players with at least 10 at bats that year. Sort the dataframe from highest batting average to lowest, and then by playerid alphabetically. Show the top 5 results in your report.__\n",
        "\n",
        "Note: A batting average is meant to measure how often a player puts the ball in play and gets to base safely. For this task, use a simplified version of batting average defined as the sum of hits (labeled 'H') divided by number of at bats (labeled 'AB').\n",
        "\n",
        "Here we can create a new column, using the already established columns for hits and at bats to calculate and save the batting average. Then we filter out the rows in which players had less than 10 at bats and sort the columns by batting average and then their player id. Here we find the highest batting average happened in 1929 with a .51 batting average."
      ],
      "id": "9ecd459a"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Include and execute your code here\n",
        "results_per_year = results.with_columns(batting_average = pl.col(\"H\") / pl.col(\"AB\")).filter(pl.col('AB') > 10).sort([\"batting_average\", 'playerID'], descending = [True, False])\n",
        "\n",
        "print(results_per_year.select(\"playerID\", 'yearID', \"AB\", 'H', \"batting_average\").head(5))"
      ],
      "id": "b84704c7",
