        "## QUESTION 2\n",
        "\n",
        "__Use the provided code above to read in the batting table. Then, with Python Polars manipulate the 'results' dataframe to calculate the batting average for each player over their entire career (all years combined). Only include players with at least 100 at bats over their entire career. Sort the dataframe from highest batting average to lowest, and then by playerid alphabetically. Show the top 5 results in your report.__ \n",
        "\n",
        "Note: A batting average is meant to measure how often a player puts the ball in play and gets to base safely. For this task, use a simplified version of batting average defined as the sum of hits (labeled 'H') divided by number of at bats (labeled 'AB').\n",
        "\n",
        "For this table I used practically the same methodology. The only thing that changed is I made sure to sum the at bats and hits for each player over all the years and then the table could be filtered by at bats (more than 100) and sorted."
      ],
      "id": "5fd9abda"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Include and execute your code here\n",
        "results_total = results.group_by('playerID').agg(pl.col('H').sum().alias('total_hits'), (pl.col('AB').sum().alias(\"at_bat\"))).with_columns(batting_average = pl.col(\"total_hits\") / pl.col(\"at_bat\")).filter(pl.col('at_bat') >= 100).sort([\"batting_average\", 'playerID'], descending = [True, False])\n",
        "\n",
        "print(results_total.select(\"playerID\", \"at_bat\", 'total_hits', \"batting_average\").head(5))"
      ],
